  "local_port": 48876,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do e-commerce companies offset last row results when paginating products?",
  "response": "E-commerce companies often implement offset-based pagination for several reasons related to user experience, performance, and the need for scalability. Here are the main reasons why they might offset last-row results when paginating products:\n\n1. **User Experience**: Offset pagination allows users to navigate through products easily. By jumping to specific pages, users can quickly access products within specific ranges without having to scroll through all available items. This is particularly useful in large catalogs.\n\n2. **Consistent State**: Offset pagination helps maintain a consistent view of products. If the underlying data changes (like products being added or removed), offset pagination allows users to see a stable set of items per page, as they are not reliant on continuously re-fetching data.\n\n3. **Performance Optimization**: When data is being fetched from a database, using an offset prevents the server from needing to calculate the entire result set during every request. Instead, it allows fetching only the necessary rows, improving performance and reducing the load on the server.\n\n4. **Flexibility for Additional Features**: Offset pagination is often easier to implement alongside sorting and filtering options. As users apply filters (like price ranges or categories), offset pagination allows for straightforward adjustments in the displayed results.\n\n5. **Handling Large Data Sets**: Many e-commerce platforms deal with extensive product catalogs. Offset pagination helps in breaking down these large sets into manageable chunks, improving loading times and overall site performance.\n\n6. **Better Caching**: It allows for better caching strategies since the same offset can be reused for pages that are commonly accessed. If a page is cached, it can be served quickly without hitting the database.\n\n7. **Real-time Inventory**: In e-commerce, where inventory can fluctuate quickly, ensuring users have access to the most relevant product listings is crucial. Pagination with offsets allows for quick resets of the page view if inventory changes occur, thus preventing users from seeing sold-out products or outdated listings.\n\nOffset pagination does come with its challenges, particularly in scenarios where the underlying dataset is constantly changing, leading to potential discrepancies (e.g., missing records). Alternatives such as keyset pagination (or \"seek\" pagination) exist, but offset pagination remains a widely used approach due to its practicality and ease of implementation.",
